{{location map+ |Serbia |float=right |width=250 |caption=Location of UNESCO World Heritage sites within Serbia and Kosovo |places= {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=42.21139 |long=20.73583|background=#FFFFFF|label=[[Our Lady of Ljeviš]]|position=right}} {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=42.59833 |long=21.19333|background=#FFFFFF|label=[[Gračanica monastery|Gračanica]]|position=right}} {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=42.661 |long=20.266|background=#FFFFFF|label=[[Patriarchate of Peć (monastery)|Patriarchate of Peć]]|position=left}} {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=42.54667 |long=20.27166|background=#FFFFFF|label=[[Visoki Dečani|Dečani]]}} {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=43.48639 |long=20.53167|background=#FFFFFF|label=[[Studenica monastery|Studenica]]|position=right}} {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=43.11889 |long=20.42278|background=#FFFFFF|label=[[Stari Ras]]|position=right}} {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=43.89917 |long=22.185|background=#FFFFFF|label=[[Gamzigrad]]|position=left}} {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=43.957778 |long=19.43|background=#FFFFFF|label=Stećci-Perućac|position=top}} {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=43.933333 |long=19.35|background=#FFFFFF|label=Stećci-Rastište|position=bottom}} {{location map~ |Serbia |lat=43.283333 |long=19.616667|background=#FFFFFF|label=Stećci-Hrta|position=bottom}} }} The [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] (UNESCO) [[World Heritage site]]s are places of importance to [[cultural heritage|cultural]] or [[natural heritage]] as described in the UNESCO World Heritage Convention, established in 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/convention/|title=UNESCO World Heritage Centre – The World Heritage Convention|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|date=25 October 2015}}</ref> [[Serbia]] succeeded the convention on 11 September 2001, following the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]].<ref name="whc.unesco.org">{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/statesparties/rs|title=Serbia|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|date=25 October 2015}}</ref>
{{As of|2017}}, there are five sites in Serbia on the list and eleven on the tentative list. The first site in Serbia to be added to the list was [[Stari Ras]] and [[Sopoćani]], inscribed at the 3rd UNESCO session in 1979.<ref name="unesco1">{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/96 |title=Stari Ras and Sopoćani – UNESCO World Heritage Centre |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |work=unesco.org |accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref> Further sites were added to the list in 1986, 2004, 2007, and 2017.<ref name="whc.unesco.org"/> All are listed as cultural sites, as determined by the organization's [[World Heritage site#Selection criteria|selection criteria]].<ref name="whc.unesco.org"/> Four out of five sites date to the [[medieval period]] while the fifth, the [[Gamzigrad]] complex, dates to [[late antiquity]]. The [[Medieval Monuments in Kosovo]] site, first added to the list in 2004 and expanded two years later, has been on UNESCO's list of [[List of World Heritage in Danger|endangered sites]] since 2006 due to difficulties in its management and conservation stemming from the region's political instability.<ref name="unesco2">{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/news/268/ |title=UNESCO World Heritage Centre – World Heritage Committee puts Medieval Monuments in Kosovo on Danger List and extends site in Andorra, ending this year’s inscriptions|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |work=unesco.org |accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref>{{efn|In February 2008, [[Kosovo]] unilaterally [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|declared independence]] from Serbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un.org/en/events/tenstories/08/kosovo.shtml |title=Ten Stories The World Should Hear More About |work=un.org |accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> It has been recognized as an independent state by over 110 countries {{as of|2017|lc=y}}.<ref name="worldatlas1">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/which-countries-recognize-kosovo-as-a-country.html |title=Which Countries Recognize Kosovo as a Country? |publisher=WorldAtlas.com |date= |accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> Serbia [[Autonomous Province of Kosovo and Metohija|considers Kosovo as a part of its sovereign territory]] while the [[United Nations]] is strictly neutral on whether or not Kosovo is an independent state. In April 2013, Serbia and Kosovo began to formalize relations under the [[Brussels Agreement (2013)|Brussels Agreement]].<ref name="worldatlas1"/> Kosovo unsuccessfully attempted to become a member of UNESCO in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/09/kosovo-fails-in-unesco-membership-bid |title=Kosovo fails in Unesco membership bid &#124; World news |publisher=''The Guardian'' |accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> In 2017, the government decided to postpone future bids.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazetaexpress.com/en/news/kosovo-gives-up-bid-to-join-unesco-173051/ |title=Kosovo gives up bid to join UNESCO |publisher=GazetaExpress |accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>}} The [[Stećci Medieval Tombstones Graveyards]] site is a transnational entry, shared with three neighboring countries.<ref name="unesco3">{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1504 |title=Stećci Medieval Tombstones Graveyards – UNESCO World Heritage Centre |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |work=unesco.org |accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref>
==World Heritage sites== UNESCO lists sites under [[World Heritage site#Selection criteria|ten criteria]]; each entry must meet at least one of the criteria. Criteria i through vi are cultural, whereas vii through x are natural.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/criteria/|title=UNESCO World Heritage Centre – The Criteria for Selection|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref> {{Legend|#D0E7FF|* Transnational site|outline=silver}} {{Legend|#FFE6BD|{{†|alt=In danger}} In danger|outline=silver}}
